# Schematic Capture

## Overview

The schematic is organized into multiple functional blocks to simplify design review, debugging, PCB layout planning, and future maintenance.

The design currently consists of the following major blocks:

* Input Protection
* Buck Convertors
* AFE (BQ76940)
* MCU (STM32)
* CAN Transceiver
* High Side Control
* SWD Programming Interface
* High Current Terminal Connections.

The modular architecture allows each subsystem to be independently verified before PCB implementation.

---

# INPUT PROTECTION

The input protection block is the first stage connected to the battery pack.

Objectives:

* Protect downstream electronics
* Suppress input transients
* Reduce switching noise
* Improve overall system robustness

This block ensures that disturbances originating from the battery pack do not directly reach sensitive analog and digital circuitry.

---

# BUCK CONVERTORS

The power architecture uses a multi-stage conversion approach.

## 58V to 12V Converter

Converts pack voltage into a regulated 12V rail.

Primary uses:

* Gate driver circuitry
* High-side control circuitry

---

## 12V to 5V Converter

Generates the intermediate 5V supply rail.

Primary uses:

* CAN communication circuitry
* Auxiliary interfaces

---

## 5V to 3.3V Converter

Generates the logic supply rail.

Primary uses:

* STM32 microcontroller
* Digital control circuitry
* BQ76940 interface circuitry

---

# AFE (BQ76940)

The Analog Front End performs battery monitoring and protection-related measurements.

Functions:

* Cell voltage monitoring
* Cell balancing support
* Fault detection
* Protection monitoring

The BQ76940 communicates with the STM32 through the I²C interface.

The integrated regulator output is also utilized for low-power system operation.

---

# MCU (STM32)

The STM32 acts as the central controller of the Battery Management System.

Responsibilities:

* Reading battery measurements
* Fault processing
* Protection decisions
* CAN communication handling
* Power state management

The MCU coordinates all major system operations.

---

# CAN TRANSCEIVER

The CAN transceiver provides communication between the Battery Management System and external vehicle electronics.

Applications:

* Charger communication
* Battery status reporting
* Fault reporting
* Diagnostic communication

The CAN interface was selected due to its high reliability in electrically noisy automotive environments.

---

# HIGH SIDE CONTROL

The high-side control block manages the charge and discharge MOSFETs.

Functions:

* Pack connection control
* Short-circuit protection
* Over-current protection
* Charger isolation
* Load isolation

High-side switching was selected to improve safety and fault isolation capabilities.

---

# SWD PROGRAMMING INTERFACE

A dedicated SWD programming header is included for firmware development and debugging.

Functions:

* Firmware programming
* Debugging
* Breakpoint analysis
* Real-time system inspection

The interface supports STM32 development using ST-LINK tools.

---

# HIGH CURRENT TERMINAL CONNECTIONS

Dedicated terminal blocks are used for battery pack and charger connections.

Reason for Selection:

* Supports high current operation
* Improved mechanical strength
* Reliable field wiring
* Simplified maintenance

These connectors form the primary power path of the Battery Management System.

